A shoe is #JustAShoeUntil it’s connected to a time, a place or a person and acts like a teleportation device to get you there. My sneakers give me memory of who I’ve been my whole life as different pairs have accompanied me into different eras of my life- from when I fell in love with basketball as a little girl watching with my dad, to playing it in high school and then most notably bringing me into my most recent era where I got to live out a childhood dream and design my own sneakers with one of my icons.  I can look at every pair in my closet and it will have a story. A lot of people say you can tell a lot about a person from looking at their bookshelf, this is very true. I also feel like this is applicable to my sneaker collection. So you see, it’s not a materialistic thing- I’ve never collected just to collect. For me it’s about material wealth…my collection supports and travels with me as I grow. A shoe is #JustAShoeUntil it becomes my vehicle to serving the world as I was designed to serve it. I met Flea when I was 38. He proposed 6 mos later on my 39th birthday & we were married 6 mos after that. Ive been working since I was 15, I love what I do. My entire 30’s despite the fact I was content & thriving in my purpose, I had an underlying stress abt the topic of kids & marriage. How am I gonna meet someone when I don’t go anywhere and hate apps?! Do I want a kid? if I don’t find someone, do I do it on my own? Do I freeze my eggs even though I don’t really want to go through the process… The questions swirled constantly. The pressure from my family & others was a trip. When I finally did get married- it was w/someone who had 2 grown kids & didn’t know if he wanted to do it again. I finally found the person I wanted to build a life with, but we were in different stages in our lives. So, I felt like the decision had been made for me. I mourned the idea of being a mom. I decided I was going to invest back into my friends kids and be the best auntie and best step mom. Growing up, my aunties were pivotal to my upbringing. Last year, after my 42nd birthday, I started to experience weird symptoms in my abdomen and attributed it to the fact that I had fibroids. I finally went to the doctor, who did find my fibroids, but also found something else or should I say someone else. 😳🥹 I won’t go into all the details, or else this is going to be the longest caption ever. The point is I was (insert all the emotions) to have an unplanned pregnancy at 42, when we weren’t even trying and genuinely surprised when it was smooth and healthy the whole way through.  I learned about so many myths that I had bought into that our culture breeds about women and a genuine lack of updated information about our bodies. I’m so happy I had the opportunity to face & debunk them. Being a mom is the most challenging work I’ve ever done- so to all the other mothers out there, I see you! I have a whole new respect for you I can’t fully articulate yet because I’m so tired my brain doesn’t work yet. And for all my other ladies out there trying or thinking about it or not- what they don’t teach us is to trust ourselves.❤️in the meantime Darius is the joy of our lives and I couldn’t be happier

So many of you reached out about my last post to tell me abt your similar experiences, it brought me to tears. So, I feel compelled to go deeper. (As deep as you can on IG) For all my ladies in their 30s/40s - think about how much has changed since our mothers generation.  My mom worked, but she didn’t have a career. She had a job so that she could provide for us, but it was a struggle. Fast forward to me, I had the luxury of exploring a passion. What I do is work - but honestly I would do it for free because it fulfills me and I LOVE it. It allows me to express myself and serve humanity and honor my Creator.  So why is it that as women we feel so guilty about following this pursuit? And when we dont meet someone to mate in the time that we deem appropriate we get down on ourselves and think maybe Im dedicating too much time to work. I know I had these thoughts- I even went through a stage where I thought I was too successful to find a partner because I thought men were intimidated by success.  So, can we just rifle through all of these MYTHS about ourselves and remove all judgement. Its hard enough to just live in this era. I think because women are striving for equality by pursuing careers and finding autonomy and establishing financial security and livelihoods outside of a man that the timelines for marriage and having children have been pushed back, and its scary. But when you get scared- who’s voice do you hear? Because if you really listen closely, its probably not yours. For me it was my mom’s. Im not here to encourage anyone to have children later on, but I do know that if you wanted to, its an option for you way longer than we allow ourselves for.  Clearly women are not prioritized or even cared for really because if we were there would be more updated research done about our bodies and our welfare in general. So be gentle and when in doubt, dedicate yourself to doing the things you love because as my BF @julieburnswalker has taught me- love is THE vehicle. When you do the things you love, it gives you information about yourself and others. It puts you in the stream that leads to the river. Just stay the course. We got this! 💜

We’ve been traveling for 7 weeks. Being a mom is such an adjustment to my body. All my energy is directed to helping this little soul navigate his first months in this world, leaving little to no energy for me to be creative in the ways that have sustained me for so long. But being in this city has sparked my inspiration and brought me back to myself a little more while having this little dude with me. It’s so exciting to turn a corner, even a little one.
